Systematic errors are characterized by the **detectability of the relationship** that connects them to their cause; their value is **higher** than the cloud of random errors (otherwise they would be confused with it). Methods to **reduce the effects of systematic errors**:
- **Correction**: calculate the error and *subtract* it from the measured value;
- **Compensation**: a physical phenomenon associated to the measurement compensates the variation of the result (e.g. a scale of the **same material** as the measurand, so both expand together with temperature);
- **Elimination**: identify the cause and remove it (e.g. work in a **thermostatic chamber** to avoid temperature variation).
